  "prompt": "Do all smartphones have Bluetooth 4.0 or BLE?",
  "response": "Not all smartphones have Bluetooth 4.0 or Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE), but the vast majority of modern smartphones do. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. **Bluetooth 4.0 and BLE Adoption**:\n   - Bluetooth 4.0, which introduced Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE), was released in 2010.\n   - Most smartphones released after 2012 support Bluetooth 4.0 or later versions, including BLE.\n   - Today, virtually all new smartphones support at least Bluetooth 4.0 or higher, with many supporting Bluetooth 5.0 or later.\n\n2. **Older Smartphones**:\n   - Devices released before 2012 may not support Bluetooth 4.0 or BLE.\n   - These older devices typically use Bluetooth 2.1 or 3.0, which do not include BLE.\n\n3. **Entry-Level or Budget Smartphones**:\n   - Some very low-cost or older budget smartphones may not include Bluetooth 4.0 or BLE, but this is increasingly rare.\n\n4. **Checking Bluetooth Version**:\n   - If you're unsure about a specific device, you can check its specifications or look for the Bluetooth version in the settings or documentation.\n\nIn summary, while most smartphones today support Bluetooth 4.0 or BLE, it's not universal, especially for older or very low-cost devices. If you're working with a smartphone made in the last decade, it likely supports Bluetooth 4.0 or later.",
